          <p>Now, assume that at the start of week <italic>n</italic> we have <italic>w</italic>1 1-week semi-urgent slots and <italic>w</italic>2 2-week semi-urgent slots waiting. If <italic>w</italic>&#x2009;=&#x2009;(<italic>w</italic>1,<italic>w</italic>2)&#x2009;&#x2208;&#x2009;<italic>B</italic> then some slots have to be performed in overtime as explained above. Thus, according to the overtime policy depicted in Fig.&#xA0;<xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig">2</xref>, the next state is given by <italic>w</italic>1<sub><italic>n</italic></sub>&#x2009;=&#x2009;<italic>w</italic>1, <italic>w</italic>2<sub><italic>n</italic></sub>&#x2009;=&#x2009;2<italic>m</italic>&#x2009;&#x2212;&#x2009;<italic>w</italic>1<sub><italic>n</italic></sub>, a point on the boundary between <italic>A</italic> and <italic>B</italic>, as pointed out with arrows in Fig.&#xA0;<xref rid="Fig3" ref-type="fig">3</xref>. Including this into transition probabilities, we derive
<disp-formula id="Equo"><alternatives><tex-math id="M30">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
