<fig id="Fig5"><label>Fig.&#xA0;5</label><caption><p><italic>&#x3B4;</italic><sup>*</sup> for <italic>CC</italic><sub>1</sub> (<italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup>&#x2009;=&#x2009;13)</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="10729_2010_9127_Fig5_HTML" id="d28e3150"/></fig><fig id="Fig6"><label>Fig.&#xA0;6</label><caption><p><italic>&#x3B4;</italic><sub><italic>M</italic></sub> for <italic>CC</italic><sub>2</sub> (<italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup>&#x2009;=&#x2009;11)</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="10729_2010_9127_Fig6_HTML" id="d28e3174"/></fig><fig id="Fig7"><label>Fig.&#xA0;7</label><caption><p><italic>&#x3B4;</italic><sup>*</sup> for <italic>CC</italic><sub>3</sub> (<italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup>&#x2009;=&#x2009;17 )</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="10729_2010_9127_Fig7_HTML" id="d28e3197"/></fig></p>
          <p>While <italic>&#x3B4;</italic><sup>*</sup> for <italic>CC</italic><sub>1</sub> and <italic>CC</italic><sub>3</sub> is straightforward&#x2014;plan 2-week slots up to <italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup> and postpone the remaining 2-week slots until next week, the policy obtained for <italic>CC</italic><sub>2</sub> is quite different. In several states it occurs that even when the number of 1-week slots exceeds <italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup>, elective slots are canceled in order to accommodate 2-week slots. This action is chosen to avoid overtime, a result of <italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup> being close to <italic>s</italic><sub><italic>min</italic></sub>. Similar to the queuing model outcomes, this shows that maintaining a cost structure similar to <italic>CC</italic><sub>2</sub>, which results in choosing an <italic>s</italic><sup>*</sup> which is close to <italic>E</italic>[<italic>R</italic>], leads to the cancellation of elective slots.</p>
        </sec>
      </sec>
